 Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bulmer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Durham): habitational name from either of two places called Bulmer, in the North Yorkshire and Essex, or from Boulmer in Northumberland. The Yorkshire place, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Bolemere</i>, is named in Old English with <i>bula</i> ‘bull’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake’, as is Boulmer; the Essex placename, found in early records as <i>Bulenemera</i>, is from <i>bulena</i> (genitive plural of <i>bula</i>) + <i>mere</i> ‘lake’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bowmer","meanings":["English (Derbyshire): variant of   Bulmer  .","Americanized form of German   Baumer  ."]},{"name":"Bolmer","meanings":["English: variant of   Bulmer  .","Dutch: probably from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Baldemar</i>, composed of the elements <i>bald</i> ‘bold’ + <i>mar</i> ‘famous’."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":15,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705182,"age":46,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Henry de Bulmer was born about 1020, in Bulmer, Yorkshire, England as the son of Anketel de Bulmer. He married Anhetel de Powther. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1066."},"et":{"about 1020–after 1066":"umbes 1020–pärast 1066","1020–1066":"1020–1066","1026–Female":"1026–Surnud","1060–1129":"1060–1129","1040–1106":"1040–1106","0995–Male":"0995–Surnud","1129":"1129","1106":"1106","0995":"0995","1026":"1026","bef 1060":"enne 1060","1035":"1035","1066":"1066","1020":"1020","after 1066":"pärast 1066","1040":"1040","about 1020":"umbes 1020","1060":"1060","Bulmer, Yorkshire, England":"Bulmer, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1020–after 1066":"noin 1020–1066 jälkeen","1020–1066":"1020–1066","1026–Female":"1026–Kuollut","1060–1129":"1060–